1: Log of Audio-Recorded Data -- tAppendix 2: Publications Associated with the HAQL Related to Status, Corpus and Acquisition Planning -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book explores the role of language academies in preserving and revitalizing minority or endangered languages. The author studies the controversial High Academy of the Quechua Language (HAQL) in Peru, the efficacy of which has been questioned by some experts. The book delves into the positions, attitudes, ideologies and practices of the HAQL and the role it has played in language policy and planning in the Andean region. The author uses ethnographic fieldwork to support what was previously only anecdotal evidence from individuals viewing the Academy from the outside. This book would appeal to anyone studying the sociolinguistics of the Quechua language, as well as to those studying broader issues of Indigenous language policy and planning, maintenance and revitalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and culturezPeru. 0aLanguage planningzPeru. 0aLanguage policyzPeru. 0aSociolinguisticszPeru. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh  aEndangered languages.  aEthnography.  aHigh Academy of the Quechua Language.  aLanguage academy.  aLanguage ideology.  aLanguage policy and planning.  aMinority languages.  aQuechua maintenance and revitalization.1 aCerrón-Palomino, Rodolfo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066313608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060670640uhttps://doi.org/10